Vehicle Service System Using Abstraction in Java Create a Java program to manage a simple vehicle service system using abstraction. 
The program should have an abstract class named VehicleService and child classes named CarService and BikeService. 
The common service details should be stored in the abstract class, but the actual service charge calculation should be implemented by the child classes. 
This problem is designed to understand:- Class- Object- Abstraction- Abstract class- Abstract method- Concrete method- Inheritance- 
Method overriding- Runtime polymorphism Problem Requirements Abstract Class: 
VehicleService Create an abstract class named VehicleService. 
It should have the following variables: String customerName; String vehicleNumber; String serviceType; Create a concrete method: 
void displayServiceDetails() This method should display: 
Customer Name Vehicle Number Service Type Create an abstract method: 
abstract double calculateServiceCharge(); 
This method should not have a body inside the abstract class. 
The child classes should provide their own implementation.
Child Class 1: CarService Create a class named CarService that inherits the abstract class VehicleService. 
class CarService extends VehicleService It should have the following variable: double sparePartsCost; 
Override the abstract method: Page 1double calculateServiceCharge() 
For car service, calculate the charge using this formula: serviceCharge = 2000 + sparePartsCost Here, 
2000 is the fixed car service charge. Child Class 2: 
BikeService Create a class named BikeService that inherits the abstract class VehicleService. 
class BikeService extends VehicleService It should have the following variable: double sparePartsCost; 
Override the abstract method: double calculateServiceCharge() For bike service, 
calculate the charge using this formula: serviceCharge = 800 + sparePartsCost Here, 
800 is the fixed bike service charge. 
Expected Concept Abstraction The abstract class should have common details and common methods: 
abstract class VehicleService It should also have an abstract method: abstract double calculateServiceCharge(); 
The abstract method only says what should be done. The child classes decide how it should be done. 
Important Rule You cannot create an object directly for an abstract class. This is not allowed: 
VehicleService service = new VehicleService(); Instead, you should create objects for child classes: 
VehicleService service; service = new CarService(); service = new BikeService(); 
